About the project

This is my learning diary for the course Introduction to Open Data Science. I’m expecting to get a better grasp of how to started analyzing data and to learn to write more readable code. I hope that after this course my thoughts will be less all over the place and will instead have a structure of some sort in my mind that helps me tie those thoughts together. You can find my Github repository for this project here: https://github.com/muraja/IODS-project.git

I find the course book R for Health Data Science readable and useful. I noticed having a tendency to read too closely, wanting to make sure I understand all the code instead of just skimming the first chapters quickly through, so I took longer with the first chapters than I intended. I think it it might have been more time-efficient to skim them through quickly now and coming back later when doing the exercises, but it still felt helpful: it clarified some of the confusion I’ve experienced when facing errors in my code (even those I resolved), and I got ideas for writing better, more readable and concise code. I’ve found dplyr functions a bit more confusing than traditional R when they have come up in forum answers, but reading through the first chapters made me more comfortable with this style. Now I’m curious to learn more and to get to write some new code.

I’m used to writing in markdown and I’m quite fond of it, so testing Rmd has been very pleasing. I enjoyed starting the course with the exercise set in Rmd format. Having learned how Github works, I realized that when I need or want to share my writing, writing in RStudio and publishing in Github could be a very handy and familiar way of doing that - even if it was just text. I wish I realized to do that earlier. Rmd also makes writing about code quite delightful as pleasantly readable text can be written with embedded working code blocks. I should have tried it sooner! More ways to avoid using Word are always welcome.

Linear Regression & Model Validation

This week I practiced linear regression and studied its assumptions and their validation via diagnostic plots to better understand how it works and how it should be used correctly. Here I present the data used, graphs for understanding the data, regression model summaries, and finally, diagnostic plots for validating the use of the model.

The higher the attitude score, ie. the more positive attitude towards learning, the higher exam points can be expected. The multiple R2 is 0.1906, which means that attitude explains about 19 % of the variation of exam points. It’s noteworthy that R2 scores didn’t change much in removing the other explanatory variables, ie. the model with a single explanatory variable explains almost as much of the variance as a model with three explanatory variables. Therefore we can be confident about removing them.

Diagnostic plots

The linear regression model has the four following assumptions:

  1. linear relationship between predictors and outcome
  2. independence of residuals
  3. normal distribution of residuals
  4. equal variance of residuals

Next I’m testing these by plotting diagnostic plots: residuals vs fitted values, normal QQ-plot and residuals vs leverage.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
model3 %>% plot(which = c(1,2,5))

In the Residuals vs Fitted plot the red line is close to the dashed line, so we can interpret that linearity holds pretty well. Heteroscedasticity (change of spread) seems mild.

In the Q-Q Plot of Residuals most of the observations are along the straight line, so we can assume that the dataset is normally distributed.

In the Residuals vs Leverage plot the leverage refers to how much the coefficients, in this case attitude, would change if the observation was removed. The leverages are small and none of the values fall within the cook’s distance, so there are no influential points. This means that there are no observations that would significantly change the model coefficients if removed.

Based on these diagnostic plots the linear regression model fits the data well.

The data set in use was contains demographic attributes and exam scores in Math and Portuguese of students in two Portuguese schools. You can view the variables above and read more about the data here.

The purpose of this analysis is to use this data to study the relationships of high and low consumption of alcohol with sex, age, freetime and address. Before the analysis, I present the following hypotheses about these relationships:

  • sex: I expect more males to have high use of alcohol than females.

  • age: I expect high alcohol use to peak at 18 years old as it’s the minimum age for legally selling alcohol outside restaurants in Portugal.

  • freetime: I expect those with more free time to be more likely to have a high alcohol consumption.

  • address: I expect more student living in urban areas to have a high alcohol use than those living in rural areas.

These hypotheses are not based on any data.

Logistic regression model

Next, I’ll explore the relationship between the presented variables using logistic regression.

# creating a logistic regression model
m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + freetime + age + address, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# printing a summary of the model
summary(m)
##

From this summary I interpret that male sex, higher free time, higher age and living in a rural area are associated with high alcohol consumption. However, only sex and free time are statistically significant explanatory variables for high/low alcohol consumption.

# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)
CI <- confint(m) %>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
# print out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
cbind(OR, CI)
##                      OR       2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.007624699 0.000217794 0.2387752
## sexM        2.248741686 1.403103099 3.6345702
## freetime    1.340048165 1.052646727 1.7179838
## age         1.195665466 0.983357893 1.4594767
## addressU    0.654713215 0.379925455 1.1386999

The odds ratio means that e.g. a male is about 2.2 times as likely to have a high use of alcohol. Each unit of free time (1-5) increases the odds of high use by 34 %, each year of age by 19 %. Those living in an urban area are about 0.65 times as likely to have high use of alcohol compared to those living in a rural area. However, the confidence intervals are wide and in the statistically insignificant variables age and address it includes 1, so the odds ratio values should not be taken literally by any means!

When compared to my hypotheses, the regression model confirms my expectations in terms of sex and free time, but contradicts my expectations with age and address. I don’t repeat these in further details as these results align with the observations from the previous section.

Predictive power of the model

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

alc <- alc %>% 
  mutate(probability = probabilities) %>% 
  mutate(prediction = probability > .5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   244   15
##    TRUE     93   18

From the table we can see that the prediction would be correct 244 + 18 = 262 times and mistaken 15 + 93 = 108 times.

# initialize a plot of 'high_use' versus 'probability' in 'alc'
g <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = probability, y = high_use))

# define the geom as points and draw the plot
g + geom_point(aes(col = prediction))

table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table %>% addmargins
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.65945946 0.04054054 0.70000000
##    TRUE  0.25135135 0.04864865 0.30000000
##    Sum   0.91081081 0.08918919 1.00000000

In this table we can see the predictions as proportions. For example, using the given variables it can be correctly predicted about 66 % of the time that a student doesn’t have a high alcohol consumption, and about 4 percent of time high consumption will be predicted when the alcohol consumption is not high.

And finally, calculating the training error:

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2918919

This means that about 29 % of the predictions made using this model will be mistaken. This is better than random chance, where half the predictions would be mistaken, but neither is this impressive.

The scale() function substracts each value with the mean of the variable and divides them with the standard deviation of the variable. This way the mean of the scaled data becomes 0 and the variation better comparable.

Plotting the LDA model:

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- train$crime %>% as.numeric

#plotting the results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Investigating the optimal number of clusters

# determining the optimal number of clusters
set.seed(5461873)
twcss <- sapply(1:20, function(k){kmeans(bost, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:20, y = twcss, geom = "line")

The exercises of the week guide that the correct number of clusters is when the WCSS drops “dramatically”. I guess that means 2 here. The second choice would be 7, as the decrease is almost linear from 2 to 7.

Rerunning with two clusters:

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(bost, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(bost[,5:10], col = km$cluster)

The clusters seem to have less overlap and be quite separate from each other, so I interpret that reducing the clusters was a good thing.

PCA on standardized data

Standardize the variables in the human data and repeat the above analysis. Interpret the results of both analysis (with and without standardizing). Are the results different? Why or why not? Include captions (brief descriptions) in your plots where you describe the results by using not just your variable names, but the actual phenomena they relate to. (0-4 points)

human_std <- scale(human) # standardizing the data
pca_std <- prcomp(human_std) # performing pca

# creating axis labels
s <- pca_std %>% summary
perc <- round(100*s$importance[2, ], digits = 2)
pc_lab <- paste0(names(perc), " (", perc, "%)")

# plotting 
pca_std %>% biplot(
  main = "PCA on standardized data", 
  cex = c(0.7, 1), 
  col = c("black","red"),
  xlab = pc_lab[1], 
  ylab = pc_lab[2],
  sub = "subtext")

The results are very different. In the non-standardized plot the PC1 explains nearly all the variance, which is caused by the GNI. The other variables do not influence the PCs much because of differing scales. The standardized PCA and its plot are a lot more useful as all the variables influence the model.

Give your personal interpretations of the first two principal component dimensions based on the biplot drawn after PCA on the standardized human data. (0-2 points)

The PC1 explains 53.61 % of the variance and captures well the educational and health-related variables. The PC2 explains 16.24 % of the variance and captures the variables repre and workFM. We can see the same relationships in the correlationplot: the health and educational variables correlate a lot with each other, whereas repre and workFM do not.

There are two datasets for this week’s analysis. Both have been converted into long format, hence the L in their names. The RatsL data has 16 rats (ID) divided into 3 groups (Group) and the weight (weight) of each was measured several times during 64 days (Time).

In the bprsL dataset , short for brief psychiatric rating scale, a test score (bprs) was measured weekly (week) in 20 subjects (subject) per two treatment groups (treatment).

From the summaries we can see that the both datasets include quite a lot of variation.

Transforming categorical variables from numerical into factors:

RatsL$ID <- factor(RatsL$ID)
RatsL$Group <- factor (RatsL$Group)

bprsL$treatment <- factor(bprsL$treatment)
bprsL$subject <- factor(bprsL$subject)

First, plotting RatsL data:

library(ggplot2)

There seems to be an increasing trend in weight in each group, but the groups have notably different starting weights. Group one seems to increase in weight less than groups 2 and 3.

Next, standardizing the data and plotting it:

RatsL <- RatsL %>% 
  group_by(Time) %>% 
  mutate(stdprs = scale(weight)) %>% 
  ungroup

ggplot(RatsL, aes(x = Time, y = stdprs, group = ID)) +

Honestly, I don’t know what this adds that we couldn’t see from the previous plot.

Moving on to a summary graph:

n <- 16 # sample size

# creating a summary dataset
RatsLS <- RatsL %>% 
  group_by(Group, Time) %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(weight), se = (sd(weight)/sqrt(n))) %>% 
  ungroup
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# plotting the summary
RatsLS %>% ggplot(
  aes(x = Time, y = mean, shape = Group, col = Group)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme(legend.position = "top") +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Time (days)", 
                     breaks = seq(0, 60, 10)) +
   geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-se, ymax=mean+se, linetype="1"), width=1) +
  geom_point(size = 1) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(weight) +/- se(weight)")

The summary graph shows us group averages and their standard errors instead of individuals. This makes the graph the easier to read the bigger the data.

Next, checking for outliers in the data using box plots:

outlaw_rat <- RatsL %>% 
  filter(Time > 1) %>% # removing baseline
  group_by(ID, Group) %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(weight)) %>% 
  ungroup
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'ID'. You can override using the `.groups`
## argument.
outlaw_rat %>% ggplot(
  aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", shape = 23, size = 2, fill = "pink") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(weight, days 1-64")

Seems that each group has an outlier. I’m dubious of removing anything from such a small sample, but I’m gonna do it anyway for practice and replot.

outlaw_rat1 <- outlaw_rat %>% filter(mean > 240, # group 1 outlier
                                     mean < 550, # group 2 outlier
                                     mean > 500 | Group != 3) 
                                                 # group 3 outlier
# plotting
outlaw_rat1 %>% ggplot(
  aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", shape = 23, size = 2, fill = "pink") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(weight, days 1-64")

Yay, done. Now, it’s obvious enough just from the graphs that these groups of rats have very different weight, but let’s test that quantitatively anyway for the fun of it. Performing a pairwise t-test:

library(rstatix)
## Warning: package 'rstatix' was built under R version 4.1.3
##

##     select
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
outlaw_rat1 %>%
  pairwise_t_test(mean ~ Group, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")

As the test shows, the groups have different weight at amusingly low p-values.

Finally, calculating a linear model for the data:

# loading the starting weight of the rats
baseline <- RatsL %>% filter(Time==1) %>% select(weight) %>% as.vector

# adding the baseline weight as a column to a data frame
outlaw_rat2 <- outlaw_rat %>% 
  mutate(baseline = baseline$weight)

# calculating a linear model for the data
rat_fit <- lm(mean ~ baseline + Group, data = outlaw_rat2)

rat_fit %>% anova
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: mean
##           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq   F value   Pr(>F)    
## baseline   1 253625  253625 1859.8201 1.57e-14 ***
## Group      2    879     439    3.2219  0.07586 .  
## Residuals 12   1636     136                       
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The ANOVA table shows us that the baseline weight is strongly related to the later weight measurements, whereas with a p-value of about 0.076 we cannot be very confident in saying that the groups had a difference in weight gain.
